**Ji'an City Announces 2026 High School Entrance Exam Rules: Geography and Biology Included in Total Score with New Bonus Policies**
The Jianshi Education and Sports Bureau in Ji'an City, Jiangxi Province, issued the 2026 High School Entrance Examination regulations on June 5, 2026. Key changes include Geography and Biology exams for 2026 candidates being scored at 50 points each (totaling 100 points) and included in the total score, whereas starting from the 2025 freshman cohort (entering exams in 2028), these subjects will shift to a computer-based format with letter grades (A-D) and will no longer count toward the total score. The 2027 exam serves as a transition year where specific categories of students, such as returnees from outside the province, must take the computer-based test with raw scores counted toward the total. The Grade 9 cultural exam is scheduled for June 17-19, with Geography and Biology exams for Grade 8 on June 20. The Grade 9 exam subjects and scores are: Chinese (120), Math (120), English (120, including 20 for listening), Physics (80), Chemistry (70), Morality and Rule of Law (80), History (80), and Physical Education (60). Students with hearing disabilities may apply to be exempted from the English listening test, with their total English score calculated as the written score multiplied by 1.2. Admission policies mandate that public and private high schools recruit within their designated local areas, with 70% of quotas for top-tier high schools (Ji'an No. 1 High School and Bailuzhou Middle School) allocated to local junior high schools. Bonus points of 10 are available for children of rural families with one or two daughters (born before 2016), overseas Chinese, and ethnic minorities in concentrated areas, though candidates can only claim the highest single bonus. The document also outlines strict prohibitions against early recruitment, cross-region recruitment, and the use of social training institutions for student selection.
Original language: zh
Publish date: June 05, 2026 07:51 AM
Source:[凤凰网（凤凰新媒体）](https://jx.ifeng.com/c/8the5vtj1nL)

**Chiayi City 7 Students Score Perfect on Junior High Exam; Peihsing Junior High Claims 4**
On June 5, 2026, the results of the Junior High School Basic Competency Assessment (國中會考) were released, revealing that 7 students in Chiayi City achieved the top score of 5A10+ with a perfect 6-level score in the essay section. According to the report by Liberty Times Net, 4 of these top performers are from Peihsing Junior High School, where Principal Lin Shih-ching posed with the students. Among the Peihsing students, Wang Shih-hua and Liu Po-chun were admitted to the Chiayi High School Science Class; Wang Shih-hua previously participated in the Physics Olympiad training camp, while Liu Po-chun has a strong interest in advanced mathematics. The other three students achieving the perfect score are Tang Chen-yu from Chia Hua Private School, Lin Hsin-wei from Minsheng Junior High School, and Huang Yi-chang from Chiayi Junior High School. Tang Chen-yu excelled in science fairs with a project on 'Preparation and Antibacterial Effect of Left-Handed Fragrant Essential Oil.' Lin Hsin-wei attributes her success to daily reading and reviewing basic concepts, having won multiple language and Hakka arts competitions. Huang Yi-chang won first place in the Chiayi City Science Exhibition Physics category and a special excellence award in a national music competition, crediting his success to reading science fiction and playing badminton and chess.
Original language: zh
Publish date: June 05, 2026 06:44 AM
Source:[Liberty Times Net](https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/ChiayiCity/breakingnews/5461820)

**Three Students at Chung Hsing Junior High Achieve Perfect 5A10+ Scores in National Exam**
On June 5, 2026, Chung Hsing Junior High School in Nantou County announced its National Junior High School Academic Proficiency Test results, with 47 students achieving a 5A grade. Among them, three students—Li Ming-Yu (male), Lin Ting-Jun (male), and Li Yen-Hui (female)—scored 5A10+, the highest possible score, including a Level 5 in writing. According to the school, Li Ming-Yu, who has a strong interest in science and mathematics, was admitted to the Science Class at Taichung No. 1 High School prior to the results. Lin Ting-Jun, not in a gifted class, outperformed his mock exam results and was described as a 'dark horse' by teachers. Li Yen-Hui, a student in the language gifted program, excels in academics and is also recognized as the school's 'fastest runner,' consistently placing in the top six in the 100-meter sprint at annual sports meets. The article notes that Nantou County's overall 5A results were similar to the previous year, with some schools seeing a slight decrease due to the high reading volume in this year's exam, which disadvantaged students without strong reading habits or speed.
