**Chinese AI Model SU-01 Wins Gold in Math and Physics Olympiads Without External Tools**
The Shanghai AI Laboratory (Shanghai AI Lab) announced the SU-01 model, a 30B-A3B architecture capable of achieving gold-medal performance in the International Mathematical Olympiad (IMO) and International Physics Olympiad (IPhO) without external tools or code execution. In the 66th IMO (2025) and USAMO (2026), SU-01 scored 35 points, exceeding the gold-medal threshold; notably, on USAMO 2026 Question 3, the model achieved a perfect score while human participants averaged only 0.01 points, with no human scoring above 5. In IPhO 2024 and 2025, the model also surpassed gold-medal standards. The achievement validates the lab's 'general-specialized fusion' approach, which uses a 'generate-verify-correct' mechanism to enable general-sized models to perform expert-level scientific reasoning. Training involved three steps: (1) behavior shaping using 338,000 high-quality solution trajectories via reverse perplexity curriculum supervised fine-tuning; (2) capability enhancement through 200-step two-stage reinforcement learning, including proof-level reward models; and (3) reasoning extension via multi-round self-verification and correction loops. On the ProofBench benchmark, SU-01 scored 57.6% in direct generation, rising to 70.2% after reasoning extension—significantly outperforming same-sized models and approaching Gemini 3.1 Pro Thinking. During USAMO 2026 reasoning, the model generated proofs averaging 106,000 tokens, with correction phases lasting 83,000 tokens. The model also succeeded on AMO-Bench and FrontierScience benchmarks, demonstrating cross-disciplinary transferability. SU-01 builds on the SAGE architecture, integrating fast intuition and slow logical reasoning for 'AGI for Science'.
