# Wikipedia Extract For Forecasting

## Why This Page Matters
This page provides background on the IMO's structure, scoring, and historical achievements, including references to perfect scores (42/42). It helps establish a base rate for how often perfect scores occur, which is directly relevant to forecasting the 2026 IMO.

---

## Key Facts

### Scoring Structure
- Maximum score: **42 points** (6 problems × 7 points each)
- Competition held over 2 days, 3 problems per day, 4.5 hours per day
- Calculators banned

### Perfect Score (42/42) Historical References
- **Ciprian Manolescu (Romania)**: Achieved a perfect score all **three times** he participated — 1995, 1996, 1997. Described as having done so "more times than anybody else in the history of the competition."
- **Eugenia Malinnikova (Soviet Union)**: Scored 42 in IMO 1990 and IMO 1991 (41 in 1989).
- **Zhuo Qun Song (Canada)**: Five gold medals including **one perfect score in 2015**.
- **Luxembourg**: 1-member team had a perfect score in **1981**.
- **United States in 1994**: Entire team scored perfectly — the only time a full team of 6 all achieved perfect scores (also noted for China in 2022, though the page says "entire team score perfectly" for USA 1994 and China 2022, and Luxembourg's 1-member team in 1981).

### Team-Level Perfect Score Events
- "The only countries to have their entire team score perfectly in the IMO were the **United States in 1994**, **China in 2022**, and **Luxembourg**, whose 1-member team had a perfect score in **1981**."

### China's All-Members-Gold Years (relevant context for 2026, hosted by China)
- China achieved all-members-gold 16 times: 1992, 1993, 1997, 2000–2002, 2004, 2006, 2009–2011, 2019, 2021–2023, 2025.

### 2026 IMO
- Scheduled for **Shanghai, China, July 10–21, 2026**

---

## Relevant Tables And Structured Data

### Notable Perfect Score Instances (from text, not a dedicated table)

| Year | Individual/Team | Score | Notes |
|------|----------------|-------|-------|
| 1981 | Luxembourg (1-member team) | 42/42 | Only member scored perfectly |
| 1994 | USA full team (6 members) | 42/42 each | Only full 6-member team to all score perfectly |
| 1995 | Ciprian Manolescu (Romania) | 42/42 | 1st of 3 consecutive perfect scores |
| 1996 | Ciprian Manolescu (Romania) | 42/42 | 2nd consecutive |
| 1997 | Ciprian Manolescu (Romania) | 42/42 | 3rd consecutive |
| 1990 | Eugenia Malinnikova (USSR) | 42/42 | Also 42 in 1991 |
| 1991 | Eugenia Malinnikova (USSR) | 42/42 | |
| 2015 | Zhuo Qun Song (Canada) | 42/42 | Among his 5 gold medals |
| 2022 | China full team (6 members) | 42/42 each | Second full team to score perfectly |

*Note: The Wikipedia page does not provide a comprehensive year-by-year table of how many individuals scored 42/42 at each IMO. The above are only the instances explicitly mentioned in the article text.*

### All-Time Medal Table (Top 10 Countries, through 2025)

| Rank | Nation | Gold | Silver | Bronze | Total |
|------|--------|------|--------|--------|-------|
| 1 | China (CHN) | 191 | 37 | 6 | 234 |
| 2 | United States (USA) | 156 | 121 | 30 | 307 |
| 3 | Russia (RUS) | 106 | 62 | 12 | 180 |
| 4 | South Korea (KOR) | 99 | 85 | 28 | 212 |
| 5 | Hungary (HUN) | 90 | 177 | 117 | 384 |
| 6 | Romania (ROU) | 88 | 161 | 112 | 361 |
| 7 | Soviet Union (URS) | 77 | 67 | 45 | 189 |
| 8 | Vietnam (VNM) | 71 | 120 | 86 | 277 |
| 9 | Great Britain (GBR) | 59 | 125 | 133 | 317 |
| 10 | Bulgaria (BGR) | 57 | 133 | 124 | 314 |

---

## Useful Caveats / Gaps

- **No year-by-year perfect score count table** is present on this Wikipedia page. The page does not systematically list how many individuals scored 42/42 in each edition of the IMO.
- The specific instances of perfect scores mentioned are anecdotal/biographical, not exhaustive.
- The page covers through **2025** in some statistics but does not provide 2025 perfect score counts.
- Problem difficulty varies year to year, which directly affects how many perfect scores are possible — this is not quantified in the article.
- The 2026 IMO is hosted by **China (Shanghai)**, which historically performs very strongly and has achieved team-wide perfect scores (2022). Host country context may be relevant but the article does not discuss how hosting affects outcomes.
- Russia has been competing under restrictions since 2022 (remote, excluded from team rankings), which may affect the competitive field.
- The article notes that in 2025, AI systems (OpenAI, Google DeepMind) claimed gold-medal-level performance, but mathematicians cautioned these claims were not based on reproducible conditions — AI does not participate as a contestant.

---

