# Wikipedia Extract For Forecasting

## Why This Page Matters
This page provides background on the IMO's structure, scoring, and historical achievements, including references to perfect scores (42/42). It helps establish a base rate for how often perfect scores occur, which is directly relevant to forecasting the 2026 IMO.

---

## Key Facts

### Scoring Structure
- Maximum score: **42 points** (6 problems × 7 points each)
- Competition held over 2 days, 3 problems per day, 4.5 hours per day
- Calculators banned

### Perfect Score (42/42) Historical References
- **Ciprian Manolescu (Romania)**: Achieved a perfect score all **three times** he participated — 1995, 1996, 1997. Described as having done so "more times than anybody else in the history of the competition."
- **Eugenia Malinnikova (Soviet Union)**: Scored 42 in IMO 1990 and IMO 1991 (41 in 1989).
- **Zhuo Qun Song (Canada)**: Five gold medals including **one perfect score in 2015**.
- **Luxembourg**: 1-member team had a perfect score in **1981**.
- **United States in 1994**: Entire team scored perfectly — the only time a full team of 6 all achieved perfect scores (also noted for China in 2022, though the page says "entire team score perfectly" for USA 1994 and China 2022, and Luxembourg's 1-member team in 1981).

### Team-Level Perfect Score Events
- "The only countries to have their entire team score perfectly in the IMO were the **United States in 1994**, **China in 2022**, and **Luxembourg**, whose 1-member team had a perfect score in **1981**."

### China's All-Members-Gold Years (relevant context for 2026, hosted by China)
- China achieved all-members-gold 16 times: 1992, 1993, 1997, 2000–2002, 2004, 2006, 2009–2011, 2019, 2021–2023, 2025.

### 2026 IMO
- Scheduled for **Shanghai, China, July 10–21, 2026**

---

