## Useful Caveats / Gaps

- **No year-by-year perfect score count table** is present on this Wikipedia page. The page does not systematically list how many individuals scored 42/42 in each edition of the IMO.
- The specific instances of perfect scores mentioned are anecdotal/biographical, not exhaustive.
- The page covers through **2025** in some statistics but does not provide 2025 perfect score counts.
- Problem difficulty varies year to year, which directly affects how many perfect scores are possible — this is not quantified in the article.
- The 2026 IMO is hosted by **China (Shanghai)**, which historically performs very strongly and has achieved team-wide perfect scores (2022). Host country context may be relevant but the article does not discuss how hosting affects outcomes.
- Russia has been competing under restrictions since 2022 (remote, excluded from team rankings), which may affect the competitive field.
- The article notes that in 2025, AI systems (OpenAI, Google DeepMind) claimed gold-medal-level performance, but mathematicians cautioned these claims were not based on reproducible conditions — AI does not participate as a contestant.

