# SerpAPI Scraped Research

## Official IMO resolution sources
- The 2025 IMO (66th edition) was held July 10–20, 2025, on the Sunshine Coast of Australia. 110 countries and 630 students competed. Source: https://maa.org/news/usa-earns-second-place-at-66th-internationalmathematical-olympiad/
- The 2026 IMO (67th edition) is scheduled for Shanghai, China, July 10–21, 2026. Source: https://www.imo2026.com/
- The imo-official.org results page for 2025 individual results was scraped but redirected to India's individual results page rather than the full 2025 results. No complete list of 2025 perfect scorers was extracted.
- From India's 2025 results: Top scorer Kanav Talwar scored 37/42 (rank 9, 98.7%). No Indian contestant scored 42/42 in 2025. The highest Indian score in 2025 was 37. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/individual/country/IND/
- From India's 2024 results: Top scorer Adhitya Mangudy Venkata Ganesh scored 35/42 (rank 5, 99.3%). No Indian contestant scored 42/42 in 2024.
- From India's 2023 results: Arjun Gupta and Atul Shatavart Nadig both scored 37/42 (rank 12, 98.2%). No Indian contestant scored 42/42 in 2023.
- From India's 2022 results: Top scorer Pranjal Srivastava scored 34/42 (rank 38, 93.7%). No Indian contestant scored 42/42 in 2022.
- The full 2025 IMO individual results page (all contestants) was not successfully scraped — only India's subset was returned.

## Historical perfect score base rates
- Maximum IMO score: 42 points (6 problems × 7 points each). Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Mathematical_Olympiad
- Notable historical perfect score (42/42) instances mentioned on Wikipedia:
  - 1981: Luxembourg's sole team member scored 42/42.
  - 1990: Eugenia Malinnikova (USSR) scored 42/42.
  - 1991: Eugenia Malinnikova (USSR) scored 42/42.
  - 1994: Entire USA team of 6 members each scored 42/42 — the only time a full 6-member team all achieved perfect scores.
  - 1995, 1996, 1997: Ciprian Manolescu (Romania) scored 42/42 in all three participations — described as "more times than anybody else in the history of the competition."
  - 2015: Zhuo Qun Song (Canada) scored 42/42 (one of his 5 gold medals).
  - 2022: Entire China team of 6 members each scored 42/42 — second full team to score perfectly.
- Wikipedia does NOT provide a comprehensive year-by-year table of how many individuals scored 42/42 at each IMO. The instances above are only those explicitly mentioned in biographical/notable sections.
- China achieved all-members-gold 16 times: 1992, 1993, 1997, 2000–2002, 2004, 2006, 2009–2011, 2019, 2021–2023, 2025. Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Mathematical_Olympiad
- The 2025 IMO had a notably hard P6 (problem 6): "Last year the gap was v big compared to the avg year" between gold and perfect score, per Manifold commenter Bayesian. Source: https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod
- From India's historical data, no Indian contestant has scored 42/42 in any year from 2013–2025 in the scraped data.

## Prediction markets and forecasting
- Manifold market "How many perfect scores will there be at IMO 2026?" exists at https://manifold.markets/aidan0626/how-many-perfect-scores-will-there — the scrape landed on a related AI perfect score market instead of the specific human perfect score count market. The specific numerical distribution/odds for that market were NOT extracted.
- Manifold market "Perfect score achieved by an AI model in the International Math Olympiad (IMO) 2026?": Current probability not explicitly stated in the extracted text, but comments reference it being debated. The market has 54 comments, 357 holders, 3.6k trades. Source: https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod
- Related Manifold markets: "Open-Source AI model gets perfect IMO 2026 score?" at 44% chance; "Gemini perfect score on IMO 2026?" at 47% chance. Source: https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod
- Polymarket "AI wins IMO gold medal in 2026?": 82% chance as of the scrape (updated Jun 5, 2026). Volume: $5,472. Market opened Nov 12, 2025. Source: https://polymarket.com/event/ai-wins-imo-gold-medal-in-2026
- Note: The Manifold market specifically about the NUMBER of human perfect scores at IMO 2026 was not successfully scraped for its actual probability distribution.

## IMO 2026 event details and context
- IMO 2026 is the 67th session, scheduled July 10–21, 2026, in Shanghai, China. Hosted at Shanghai High School (No.989, Baise Road, Shanghai). Organized by Chinese Mathematical Society. Source: https://www.imo2026.com/
- Expected participation: 100+ countries/territories, 1000+ participants, 10000+ followers. Source: https://www.imo2026.com/
- Contact: 67imo2026@sina.com. Annual Regulations document available at https://www.imo2026.com/file/IMO2026-AnnualRegulations.pdf
- The official IMO 2026 website does not yet contain results or problem information (event has not occurred as of the scrape).
- IMO 2026 is the first time China hosts since... (not specified on the site). China last hosted IMO in 1990 (Beijing).

## Recent IMO results and difficulty analysis
- 2025 IMO (66th): Held July 10–20, 2025, Sunshine Coast, Australia. 110 countries, 630 students. USA scored 216 points total (second place). USA team: 5 gold medals, 1 silver medal. Tiger Zhang and Alexander Wang placed in top 10 individually. Source: https://maa.org/news/usa-earns-second-place-at-66th-internationalmathematical-olympiad/
- 2025 IMO top individual score from India: 37/42 (Kanav Talwar, rank 9). No 42/42 scores from India in 2025.
- 2025 P6 was described as "especially hard" — "the gap was v big compared to the avg year" between gold-medal level and perfect score. Source: Manifold comment by user Bayesian at https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod
- 2022 IMO: China's entire 6-member team scored 42/42 — a historically rare event. Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Mathematical_Olympiad
- 1994 IMO: USA's entire 6-member team scored 42/42 — the first time a full team achieved this. Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Mathematical_Olympiad
- Perfect scores are highly variable year to year, depending heavily on problem difficulty (especially P3 and P6). Many gold medalists across multiple years have 0 or 1 perfect scores. Source: Manifold comment by DottedCalculator at https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod
- No year-by-year count of total perfect scorers across all contestants is available from the scraped sources.

## AI at IMO context
- In 2025, experimental large language models from OpenAI and Google DeepMind scored 35/42 points on the 2025 IMO problems, solving 5 of 6 problems with full natural-language proofs under timed conditions. Results verified by former IMO medalists and official coordinators. Source: https://polymarket.com/event/ai-wins-imo-gold-medal-in-2026
- AI systems did NOT achieve a perfect score (42/42) at the 2025 IMO — they scored 35/42 (gold-medal level but not perfect). Source: Polymarket AI summary and Manifold bot comment.
- Polymarket gives 82% probability that an AI wins IMO gold medal in 2026 (resolves via IMO Grand Challenge or AIMO prize, not the official IMO contestant results). Source: https://polymarket.com/event/ai-wins-imo-gold-medal-in-2026
- Manifold markets give 44% for open-source AI perfect score at IMO 2026, 47% for Gemini perfect score at IMO 2026. Source: https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod
- AI does NOT participate as an official contestant in the IMO — AI performance is evaluated separately via the IMO Grand Challenge and AIMO prize frameworks, not through the official contestant results at imo-official.org. The forecasting question resolves based on human contestant scores only.
- The resolution question (human perfect scores at imo-official.org) is separate from AI performance questions. AI achieving gold-medal level does not directly affect the count of human perfect scorers, though it may influence problem difficulty selection by organizers.

