dals awarded. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/\n- 1987 IMO: 42 countries, 237 contestants, gold cutoff = 42, max score = 42. 22 gold medals awarded. Note: Gold cutoff = 42 means ALL gold medalists scored 42/42 — 22 perfect scores in 1987. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/\n- 1986 IMO: 37 countries, 210 contestants, gold cutoff = 34, max score = 42. 18 gold medals awarded. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/\n- 1985 IMO: 38 countries, 209 contestants, gold cutoff = 34, max score = 42. 14 gold medals awarded. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/\n- 1984 IMO: 34 countries, 192 contestants, gold cutoff = 40, max score = 42. 14 gold medals awarded. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/\n- 1983 IMO: 32 countries, 186 contestants, gold cutoff = 38, max score = 42. 9 gold medals awarded. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/\n- 1982 IMO: 30 countries, 119 contestants, gold cutoff = 37, max score = 42. 10 gold medals awarded. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/\n- 1981 IMO: 27 countries, 185 contestants, gold cutoff = 41, max score = 42. 36 gold medals awarded. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/\n- KEY INSIGHT: The gold cutoff score is the minimum score for a gold medal. When the gold cutoff equals 42, ALL gold medalists scored 42/42 (e.g., 1987: 22 perfect scores). When the gold cutoff is below 42, the number of perfect scorers is a subset of gold medalists — typically far fewer than the total gold count. The results index does NOT directly list the count of 42/42 scorers for each year; that requires checking individual year results.\n- Notable years where gold cutoff was very high (close to 42), suggesting few or many perfect scores: 1987 (cutoff=42, 22 perfect scores), 1994 (cutoff=40), 1991 (cutoff=39), 1989 (cutoff=38), 1983 (cutoff=38), 1997 (cutoff=35), 2005 (cutoff=35), 2025 (cutoff=35).\n- For recent years (2015–2025), gold cutoffs ranged from 24 to 35, well below 42, meaning perfect scores are a small subset of gold medalists.\n- From India's historical data: No Indian contestant scored 42/42 in any year from 2013–2025. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/individual/country/IND/\n- Notable historical perfect score instances (from Wikipedia): 1994 — entire USA team of 6 scored 42/42; 1995–1997 — Ciprian Manolescu (Romania) scored 42/42 three times; 2015 — Zhuo Qun Song (Canada) scored 42/42; 2022 — entire China team of 6 scored 42/42. Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Mathematical_Olympiad\n- The Quora page on historical perfect scores returned no usable content.\n\n## Prediction markets and forecasting\n- Manifold market \"How many perfect scores will there be at IMO 2026?\" exists at https://manifold.markets/aidan0626/how-many-perfect-scores-will-there — specific numerical distribution/odds were NOT extracted in any scrape cycle.\n- Manifold market \"Perfect score achieved by an AI model in the International Math Olympiad (IMO) 2026?\": 54 comments, 357 holders, 3.6k trades. Source: https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod\n- Related Manifold markets: \"Open-Source AI model gets perfect IMO 2026 score?\" at 44% chance; \"Gemini perfect score on IMO 2026?\" at 47% chance. Source: https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod\n- Polymarket \"AI wins IMO gold medal in 2026?\": 82% chance (updated Jun 5, 2026). Volume: $5,472. Source: https://polymarket.com/event/ai-wins-imo-gold-medal-in-2026\n- The specific Manifold market about the NUMBER of human perfect scores at IMO 2026 has not been successfully scraped for its probability distribution.\n\n## IMO 2026 event details and context\n- IMO 2026 is the 67th session, scheduled July 10–21, 2026, in Shanghai, China. Hosted at Shanghai High School (No.989, Baise Road, Shanghai). Organized by Chinese Mathematical Society. Source: https://www.imo2026.com/\n- Expected participation: 100+ countries/territories, 1000+ participant