## Recent IMO results and difficulty analysis
- 2025 IMO gold cutoff: 35/42. 72 gold medals. 630 contestants. The gap between gold cutoff (35) and perfect score (42) is 7 points — a large gap suggesting few perfect scores in 2025. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/
- 2024 IMO gold cutoff: 29/42. 58 gold medals. 609 contestants. Gap of 13 points from gold cutoff to perfect score. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/
- 2023 IMO gold cutoff: 32/42. 54 gold medals. 618 contestants. Gap of 10 points. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/
- 2022 IMO gold cutoff: 34/42. 44 gold medals. 589 contestants. China's entire 6-member team scored 42/42 — a historically rare event. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/ and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Mathematical_Olympiad
- 2021 IMO gold cutoff: 24/42. 52 gold medals. 619 contestants. Very low cutoff suggests hard problems; gap of 18 points from cutoff to perfect. Source: https://www.imo-official.org/results/
- 2025 P6 described as "especially hard" — "the gap was v big compared to the avg year" between gold-medal level and perfect score. Source: Manifold comment at https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod
- Perfect scores are highly variable year to year, depending heavily on problem difficulty (especially P3 and P6). Source: Manifold comment by DottedCalculator at https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod
- The gold cutoff data from imo-official.org provides an indirect signal: years with gold cutoff near 42 tend to have more perfect scores; years with gold cutoff far below 42 tend to have fewer. However, the exact count of 42/42 scorers per year is not directly listed in the results index.
- 1987 is a confirmed outlier: gold cutoff = 42, meaning all 22 gold medalists scored 42/42.
- For the period 2015–2025, gold cutoffs ranged 24–35, all well below 42, consistent with relatively few perfect scores per year in recent times.

## AI at IMO context
- In 2025, experimental LLMs from OpenAI and Google DeepMind scored 35/42 on the 2025 IMO problems (gold-medal level, not perfect). Source: https://polymarket.com/event/ai-wins-imo-gold-medal-in-2026
- AI does NOT participate as an official contestant in the IMO — AI performance is evaluated separately via the IMO Grand Challenge and AIMO prize frameworks. The forecasting question resolves based on human contestant scores at imo-official.org only.
- Polymarket gives 82% probability that an AI wins IMO gold medal in 2026 (via IMO Grand Challenge or AIMO prize). Source: https://polymarket.com/event/ai-wins-imo-gold-medal-in-2026
- Manifold markets: 44% for open-source AI perfect score at IMO 2026, 47% for Gemini perfect score at IMO 2026. Source: https://manifold.markets/Bayesian/perfect-score-achieved-by-an-ai-mod
- AI achieving gold-medal level does not directly affect the count of human perfect scorers, though it may influence problem difficulty selection by organizers (potentially making problems harder to distinguish AI from human performance).

